00:26:14.390 --> 00:26:15.830
to when they cross.

00:26:15.830 --> 00:26:17.450
These are all
annualized, remember.

00:26:17.450 --> 00:26:20.972
So you're asking the question,
over a 10-year period what

00:26:20.972 --> 00:26:22.430
is the average
interest rate you're

00:26:22.430 --> 00:26:24.410
going to get paid by
the US Government,

00:26:24.410 --> 00:26:25.827
versus over a one
year period what

00:26:25.827 --> 00:26:28.118
is the interest rate you're
going to get paid by the US

00:26:28.118 --> 00:26:28.670
Government?

00:26:28.670 --> 00:26:29.170
That's all.

00:26:31.760 --> 00:26:34.810
Now let me talk
about volatility.

00:26:34.810 --> 00:26:38.340
These are monthly estimates
of US Stock Market

00:26:38.340 --> 00:26:40.800
daily volatility
from 1926 to 1997.

00:26:40.800 --> 00:26:44.850
So every month I've
got 20 days or 21 days.

00:26:44.850 --> 00:26:46.525
I'm going to take
the daily returns

00:26:46.525 --> 00:26:49.020
and calculate the
standard deviation

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:53.190
for those daily returns, and I
plot it and it looks like this.

00:26:53.190 --> 00:26:55.620
Now, these are monthly, so
if you want to annualize it

00:26:55.620 --> 00:26:58.170
you have to multiply it
by the square root of 12

00:26:58.170 --> 00:27:00.690
to get the annualized
volatility.

00:27:00.690 --> 00:27:04.650
But the point of this is that
there are periods of time where

00:27:04.650 --> 00:27:07.200
the market is
extremely volatile,

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:10.390
and there are periods of time
where it's relatively quiet.

00:27:10.390 --> 00:27:13.710
And if I would have extended
this to the most recent period,

00:27:13.710 --> 00:27:16.890
you would see that within
the last several weeks

00:27:16.890 --> 00:27:21.600
we had a spike that was about
as big as this spike over here.

00:27:21.600 --> 00:27:23.894
Anybody know what this spike is?

00:27:23.894 --> 00:27:24.810
You can sort of guess.

00:27:24.810 --> 00:27:27.240
Yeah, October 1987.

00:27:27.240 --> 00:27:29.910
That was the big stock
market crash that

00:27:29.910 --> 00:27:32.430
occurred during that month.

00:27:32.430 --> 00:27:35.490
Volatility shot way up during
that month-- lots of risk.

00:27:35.490 --> 00:27:37.680
And right now we're
in a situation where

00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:41.550
there is lots of risk as well.

00:27:41.550 --> 00:27:44.910
Now, I'm going to just
conclude my overview

00:27:44.910 --> 00:27:49.380
with a few interesting anomalies
that I want to tease you with

00:27:49.380 --> 00:27:51.120
to get you to think
a little bit more

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:54.150
carefully about stock markets.

00:27:54.150 --> 00:27:55.680
What I'm going to
show you are just

00:27:55.680 --> 00:27:59.970
a bunch of factoids, factoids
meaning that they are

00:27:59.970 --> 00:28:02.110
empirical facts in the data.

00:28:02.110 --> 00:28:06.990
But if you change some of
the assumptions or the sample

00:28:06.990 --> 00:28:10.320
that you use, these
facts could change.

00:28:10.320 --> 00:28:13.140
So these are not
universal constants

00:28:13.140 --> 00:28:15.990
that, for some theoretical
reason, has to be true.

00:28:15.990 --> 00:28:18.870
This is just
properties of the data.

00:28:18.870 --> 00:28:21.390
What I've done here is
to take all the stocks

00:28:21.390 --> 00:28:27.420
in the NYSE, Amex, and
NASDAQ from 1964 to 2004.

00:28:27.420 --> 00:28:30.420
And on a monthly
basis, I'm going

00:28:30.420 --> 00:28:34.080
to rank them by
market capitalization,

00:28:34.080 --> 00:28:40.230
break them up into 10 equal
numbers of securities,

00:28:40.230 --> 00:28:46.680
and then average the
returns in those deciles

00:28:46.680 --> 00:28:49.410
and then compute it
over time and then

00:28:49.410 --> 00:28:53.220
average those decile returns.

00:28:53.220 --> 00:28:55.260
That sounds a
little complicated,

00:28:55.260 --> 00:28:56.850
but pretty straightforward.

00:28:56.850 --> 00:28:59.790
Let me tell you, for example,
what this means here.

00:28:59.790 --> 00:29:05.250
This particular bin
over here is the bin

00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:10.740
of all stocks that
have the largest market

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:17.150
capitalizations among all
of the stocks in my sample.

00:29:17.150 --> 00:29:19.020
I've divided them up
into 10 equal groups.

00:29:19.020 --> 00:29:21.540
This is the largest
10th, and I'm

00:29:21.540 --> 00:29:25.680
going to compute the
returns monthly for that bin

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:28.890
and then average that
across my entire sample.

00:29:28.890 --> 00:29:33.390
And I get an annual
return of close to 10%.

00:29:33.390 --> 00:29:34.950
This is annualized now.

00:29:34.950 --> 00:29:37.080
It's not monthly-- annualized.

00:29:40.520 --> 00:29:43.940
If I now compute that
same rate of return

00:29:43.940 --> 00:29:47.360
for the smallest
stocks, the stocks

00:29:47.360 --> 00:29:50.870
that are the smallest
part of my sample--

00:29:50.870 --> 00:29:52.910
that's down here--

00:29:52.910 --> 00:29:57.260
I get a return of something
like 15% per year.

00:29:59.960 --> 00:30:04.730
15% versus 10%, that's
a huge difference.

00:30:04.730 --> 00:30:07.260
That's like a 6 percentage
point difference.

00:30:07.260 --> 00:30:12.280
No, it's more like 9%
versus 15%-plus something.

00:30:12.280 --> 00:30:15.600
Five percentage points,
500 basis points a year--

00:30:15.600 --> 00:30:20.630
that's the gap between small
stocks and large stocks.

00:30:20.630 --> 00:30:26.510
This is known as the size
effect or the size premium.

00:30:26.510 --> 00:30:30.020
Small stocks seem to do
better than large stocks.

00:30:30.020 --> 00:30:32.930
Now, there are lots of stories
you could tell about why.

00:30:32.930 --> 00:30:34.580
I'm not going to
tell those stories,

00:30:34.580 --> 00:30:37.760
but I just want you
to see the data.

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:40.160
Now, you want to know
what's weird about this?

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:41.660
What's weird about
this picture is

00:30:41.660 --> 00:30:46.260
that I'm going to change
the sample ever so slightly.

00:30:46.260 --> 00:30:48.710
What I'm going to
do is I'm going

00:30:48.710 --> 00:30:55.700
to compute this graph only
for the month of January

00:30:55.700 --> 00:30:59.495
and then for all the other
months outside of January.

00:31:01.744 --> 00:31:03.035
And I'll show you what happens.

00:31:07.120 --> 00:31:13.690
The yellow bars-- those
are the January returns,

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:18.850
and the blue bars are all
of the non-January returns.

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:22.060
So I don't really think there's
that much of a size effect

00:31:22.060 --> 00:31:24.610
once you delete the Januarys.

00:31:24.610 --> 00:31:27.700
You get a little bit of a
difference between the biggest

00:31:27.700 --> 00:31:29.590
and the smallest,
but the difference

00:31:29.590 --> 00:31:34.640
that we're talking
about now is very small.

00:31:34.640 --> 00:31:37.820
But look at the January effect.

00:31:37.820 --> 00:31:39.830
That's big.

00:31:39.830 --> 00:31:46.040
And it turns out that this
seems to be a phenomenon that

00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:50.120
has become a little bit
less pronounced recently,

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:54.650
but for many years it was
quite strong and reliable.

00:31:54.650 --> 00:31:58.760
And people actually traded
on this particular pattern,

00:31:58.760 --> 00:32:04.160
buying stocks in January,
holding them in December,

00:32:04.160 --> 00:32:08.300
and holding them until January,
or doing a spread where you

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:10.370
basically tried to go long--

00:32:10.370 --> 00:32:16.190
small stocks in December
and large stocks in December

00:32:16.190 --> 00:32:17.180
and hold that spread.

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:18.620
And then it widened.

00:32:18.620 --> 00:32:22.670
So this is a really
puzzling anomaly.

00:32:22.670 --> 00:32:25.144
Again, you can come up
with explanations for this.

00:32:25.144 --> 00:32:26.810
I'm not going to tell
you what they are.

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:30.920
You can think about them and
possibly even trade on them

00:32:30.920 --> 00:32:32.240
over the next month or so.

00:32:34.940 --> 00:32:38.630
Now, the second anomaly that
I want you to be aware of--

00:32:38.630 --> 00:32:41.270
and this, depending
on who you speak to,

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:43.010
may not be considered
an anomaly.

00:32:43.010 --> 00:32:44.480
For example, Warren
Buffett would

00:32:44.480 --> 00:32:48.890
call this genius and fact.

00:32:48.890 --> 00:32:50.990
This is the value premium.

00:32:50.990 --> 00:32:55.130
What this suggests is that
there are certain stocks that,

00:32:55.130 --> 00:32:59.150
for whatever reason, are
just simply undervalued

00:32:59.150 --> 00:33:01.340
systematically--
or, alternatively,

00:33:01.340 --> 00:33:05.720
other stocks that are
systematically overvalued.

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:09.230
The value premium is where
you take the same universe

00:33:09.230 --> 00:33:11.330
of stocks that I showed
you before, but instead

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:13.280
of sorting according to
market capitalization,

00:33:13.280 --> 00:33:15.810
you sort it according to
another characteristic.

00:33:15.810 --> 00:33:19.340
And the characteristic is
the price-equity ratio,

00:33:19.340 --> 00:33:22.340
or the reverse of that is
what you usually hear about,

00:33:22.340 --> 00:33:23.720
book-to-market--

00:33:23.720 --> 00:33:26.610
book value divided
by market value.

00:33:26.610 --> 00:33:29.480
Now, you all know what
that difference is by now.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:33.500
Book value is the
value of the company

00:33:33.500 --> 00:33:38.990
as it was initially formed
and as it accrues either cash

00:33:38.990 --> 00:33:44.240
or profitability, but based
upon its accounting book value.

00:33:44.240 --> 00:33:47.240
Whereas the market value
is what the market thinks

00:33:47.240 --> 00:33:48.830
the company is worth.

00:33:48.830 --> 00:33:50.990
And in many cases,
with technology stocks

00:33:50.990 --> 00:33:53.090
and other growth
stocks, the price

00:33:53.090 --> 00:33:58.700
gets way, way ahead of the
value of the company's assets.

00:33:58.700 --> 00:34:00.680
And so those are
situations where

00:34:00.680 --> 00:34:04.640
you've got a very large
price-to-book ratio.

00:34:04.640 --> 00:34:06.944
If you have a very large
price-to-book ratio,

00:34:06.944 --> 00:34:08.360
that means that
you're going to be

00:34:08.360 --> 00:34:12.080
on the right hand
of this spectrum.

00:34:12.080 --> 00:34:14.360
And that says,
according to this chart,

00:34:14.360 --> 00:34:18.989
that the expected rate of
return is generally pretty low.

00:34:18.989 --> 00:34:21.770
On the other hand, low
book-to-market or high

00:34:21.770 --> 00:34:23.750
book-to-price--

00:34:23.750 --> 00:34:26.639
sorry, the other way around--

00:34:26.639 --> 00:34:29.900
high book-to-market,
low price-to-book

00:34:29.900 --> 00:34:32.460
is on the left-hand side.

00:34:32.460 --> 00:34:35.420
These are what Warren
Buffett and Graham and Dodd

00:34:35.420 --> 00:34:37.040
would call "value stocks."

00:34:37.040 --> 00:34:41.270
These are stocks where you've
got lots of good book value,

00:34:41.270 --> 00:34:43.850
but somehow the market
doesn't really appreciate it.

00:34:43.850 --> 00:34:47.489
And so the price is low
relative to the book value.

00:34:47.489 --> 00:34:51.050
In other words, the
price-to-book ratio is low.

00:34:51.050 --> 00:34:52.880
And look at the returns there.

00:34:52.880 --> 00:34:55.370
The value premium
is the difference

00:34:55.370 --> 00:35:00.350
between the high price-to-book
and the low price-to-book,

00:35:00.350 --> 00:35:04.610
and you're looking at a premium
of about 600 to 700 basis

00:35:04.610 --> 00:35:07.010
points, on an annualized basis.

00:35:07.010 --> 00:35:11.840
That's a big difference,
because in both of these bins

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:16.310
it turns out the risks are
actually roughly comparable.

00:35:16.310 --> 00:35:18.890
So it's not as if the
stocks on the left

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:21.680
are way more risky than
the stocks on the right.

00:35:21.680 --> 00:35:25.190
That actually is true of the
market capitalization effect.

00:35:25.190 --> 00:35:27.890
Small stocks actually
have higher volatility

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:29.630
than large stocks.

00:35:29.630 --> 00:35:32.480
But that's not true
of value and growth.

00:35:32.480 --> 00:35:36.570
So that's another puzzle, or,
depending on who you talk to,

00:35:36.570 --> 00:35:39.640
this is a way to invest.

00:35:39.640 --> 00:35:44.300
Momentum-- this is something
that academics discovered maybe

00:35:44.300 --> 00:35:48.260
10 or 15 years ago, which
is also really anomalous.

00:35:48.260 --> 00:35:55.760
By momentum, we mean
simply last year's return.

00:35:55.760 --> 00:36:00.470
If that's positive, does it
tend to persist over the next 12

00:36:00.470 --> 00:36:01.650
months?

00:36:01.650 --> 00:36:07.040
So the stocks with low
momentum on the left-hand side

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:12.590
seem to do worse than the
stocks that have high momentum.

00:36:12.590 --> 00:36:15.380
So the momentum effect
seems to be really strong.

00:36:15.380 --> 00:36:17.180
And again, look at
that difference.

00:36:17.180 --> 00:36:20.510
That difference is something
on the order of a 15% spread,

00:36:20.510 --> 00:36:21.770
if not more.

00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:24.080
It's a very, very big spread.

00:36:24.080 --> 00:36:26.660
So this might lead you to
try to construct a trading

00:36:26.660 --> 00:36:28.890
strategy based upon this.

00:36:28.890 --> 00:36:30.710
And there are a bunch
of other anomalies

00:36:30.710 --> 00:36:33.240
that have been reported in
the academic literature.

00:36:33.240 --> 00:36:36.290
In fact, for a while,
certain academic journals

00:36:36.290 --> 00:36:39.980
were accused of never meeting an
anomaly that they didn't love,

00:36:39.980 --> 00:36:42.980
because they just kept
publishing one after another.

00:36:42.980 --> 00:36:48.590
And in a way, you have to be
a bit skeptical about this,

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:51.410
because there are so many
different ways of looking

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:53.660
at stocks, so many
characteristics.

00:36:53.660 --> 00:36:59.360
And you know that in a sample
of 100 random variables,

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:05.030
5% of them are going to be
statistically significant, even

00:37:05.030 --> 00:37:09.410
if none of them are in
terms of being significantly

00:37:09.410 --> 00:37:11.032
different from zero.

00:37:11.032 --> 00:37:13.490
So you've got to take these
anomalies with a grain of salt,

00:37:13.490 --> 00:37:15.230
but what I've
presented to you are

00:37:15.230 --> 00:37:17.000
the ones that seem
to be the most

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:19.640
persistent, the ones that
people spin stories about,

00:37:19.640 --> 00:37:22.640
the ones that people
construct mutual funds around.

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:25.580
And so you'll have to think a
little bit about whether or not

00:37:25.580 --> 00:37:27.710
you believe any of
these anomalies,

00:37:27.710 --> 00:37:29.930
but I wanted to make you
aware that they're there.

00:37:29.930 --> 00:37:34.430
And if you take
15433, investments,

00:37:34.430 --> 00:37:36.882
you'd actually end up spending
a fair bit of time digging

00:37:36.882 --> 00:37:38.840
through each one of these
to see whether or not

00:37:38.840 --> 00:37:40.730
there's something in
there that you could

00:37:40.730 --> 00:37:42.320
use for investment purposes.

00:37:45.850 --> 00:37:49.750
The last thing I want to mention
with this introductory lecture

00:37:49.750 --> 00:37:52.620
is mutual funds.

00:37:52.620 --> 00:37:58.050
These anomalies were
obviously very, very exciting

00:37:58.050 --> 00:38:00.810
from the perspective of
active portfolio management,

00:38:00.810 --> 00:38:02.951
because once you identify
one of these anomalies

00:38:02.951 --> 00:38:04.950
you could argue, I want
to take advantage of it.

00:38:04.950 --> 00:38:07.710
Of course, then the argument
that was raised earlier

00:38:07.710 --> 00:38:08.550
comes into play.

00:38:08.550 --> 00:38:10.216
If you're going to
take advantage of it,

00:38:10.216 --> 00:38:12.160
isn't that going to disappear?

00:38:12.160 --> 00:38:15.300
And the answer is, in
general, yes, it will,

00:38:15.300 --> 00:38:16.410
but it may take a while.

00:38:16.410 --> 00:38:20.010
And along the way,
you'll do quite well.

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:22.920
So the question was
asked, well, if that's

00:38:22.920 --> 00:38:25.140
the case, if there are
all these anomalies

00:38:25.140 --> 00:38:27.530
and if you can take
advantage of them,

00:38:27.530 --> 00:38:30.270
well, then mutual
fund managers ought

00:38:30.270 --> 00:38:34.560
to be able to outperform
simple buy and hold strategies.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:38.880
Because they can take
advantage of these anomalies.

00:38:38.880 --> 00:38:44.340
If you do a histogram
of mutual fund returns

00:38:44.340 --> 00:38:48.240
that are in excess
of their risks--

00:38:48.240 --> 00:38:52.080
so if you make some kind
of a simple risk adjustment

00:38:52.080 --> 00:38:55.530
and you look at the mutual
funds' additional value added

00:38:55.530 --> 00:38:58.470
above and beyond those
risk adjustments--

00:38:58.470 --> 00:39:01.650
those excess returns are
given by this histogram.

00:39:01.650 --> 00:39:07.950
For data from 1972 to 1991,
the histogram of excess returns

00:39:07.950 --> 00:39:11.700
has basically this
kind of a distribution.

00:39:11.700 --> 00:39:15.540
You've got some positives,
you've got some negatives,

00:39:15.540 --> 00:39:17.760
you've got more
negatives than positives,

00:39:17.760 --> 00:39:22.720
and on average it's
actually less than zero.

00:39:22.720 --> 00:39:28.780
Mutual funds net of fees are
actually losing money for you

00:39:28.780 --> 00:39:29.440
on average.

00:39:29.440 --> 00:39:33.640
That was the conclusion by these
academics as of a few years

00:39:33.640 --> 00:39:34.300
ago.

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:35.442
Yeah?

00:39:35.442 --> 00:39:38.117
STUDENT: In defense
of the big ones,

00:39:38.117 --> 00:39:40.820
isn't part of the
purpose to lower

00:39:40.820 --> 00:39:43.850
your risk of your portfolio
to lower the volatility?

00:39:43.850 --> 00:39:49.310
For example, you might be able
to get the return plus zero.

00:39:49.310 --> 00:39:51.289
But then the next
year you might be

00:39:51.289 --> 00:39:52.705
able to get the
return minus five.

00:39:52.705 --> 00:39:55.130
Well, I think
mutual fund managers

00:39:55.130 --> 00:40:01.360
aim to get you steady terms
that are [? being ?] exactly

00:40:01.360 --> 00:40:02.620
the term, plus zero.

00:40:02.620 --> 00:40:05.260
PROFESSOR: Well, so first of
all, that's not necessarily

00:40:05.260 --> 00:40:06.850
the objective of
every mutual fund

00:40:06.850 --> 00:40:09.760
right there are mutual
funds that are not

00:40:09.760 --> 00:40:11.260
trying to give you
lower volatility,

00:40:11.260 --> 00:40:13.180
but rather they're
trying to give you access

00:40:13.180 --> 00:40:16.960
to broader investment
vehicles and instruments.

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:19.570
So the original index
fund that was set up

00:40:19.570 --> 00:40:22.210
by Wells Fargo in the 1970s--

00:40:22.210 --> 00:40:24.820
the purpose was to
allow an investor

00:40:24.820 --> 00:40:29.530
to get access to 100 securities
without having to actually go

00:40:29.530 --> 00:40:31.589
out and buy 100 securities.

00:40:31.589 --> 00:40:33.130
STUDENT: Thereby
diversifying, right?

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:34.810
PROFESSOR: Right,
by diversifying.

00:40:34.810 --> 00:40:37.210
But it doesn't lower
the volatility,

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:39.514
except through diversification.

00:40:39.514 --> 00:40:40.180
So you're right.

