00:47:46.160 --> 00:47:48.150
you are making a decision.

00:47:48.150 --> 00:47:49.730
So what we want to
do is to see if we

00:47:49.730 --> 00:47:51.980
can think about making that
decision a little bit more

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:53.330
systematically.

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:56.250
To do that, I want to define
what I mean by a portfolio.

00:47:56.250 --> 00:47:59.450
So the definition,
in very simple terms,

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:05.480
is just a specific weighting or
combination of securities, such

00:48:05.480 --> 00:48:07.820
that the weights add up to one.

00:48:07.820 --> 00:48:10.072
It's just a way to
divide up the pie.

00:48:10.072 --> 00:48:11.780
If you've got a certain
amount of wealth,

00:48:11.780 --> 00:48:14.660
you're going to allocate it
among different securities

00:48:14.660 --> 00:48:16.280
into a portfolio.

00:48:16.280 --> 00:48:20.180
A portfolio is defined as a set
of weights of those securities

00:48:20.180 --> 00:48:22.730
where the weights add up to one.

00:48:22.730 --> 00:48:24.680
Now, this is sort
of the framework

00:48:24.680 --> 00:48:27.710
that we use in terms
of the notation.

00:48:27.710 --> 00:48:31.280
So omega, the
Greek letter omega,

00:48:31.280 --> 00:48:33.800
when you write it
as a vector, it

00:48:33.800 --> 00:48:38.100
denotes the set of weights
for your portfolio.

00:48:38.100 --> 00:48:41.750
So if you've got n securities,
then this vector omega, which

00:48:41.750 --> 00:48:45.210
is equal to omega one,
comma, omega two, dot, dot,

00:48:45.210 --> 00:48:49.800
dot, omega n, that
is a portfolio.

00:48:49.800 --> 00:48:52.490
And if you want to be clear
about how to define it,

00:48:52.490 --> 00:48:55.550
it's simply the number
of shares of security

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:59.480
I multiplied by
that price, divided

00:48:59.480 --> 00:49:04.820
by the sum of all of the
values of your securities

00:49:04.820 --> 00:49:06.980
in your entire collection.

00:49:09.570 --> 00:49:10.670
Any questions about this?

00:49:10.670 --> 00:49:12.770
Very basic stuff, but
it's important to get

00:49:12.770 --> 00:49:15.820
it right upfront.

00:49:15.820 --> 00:49:17.910
Now, by the way,
the number of shares

00:49:17.910 --> 00:49:22.940
NI, I'm going to let
that be a real number,

00:49:22.940 --> 00:49:28.660
meaning it could be zero, it
could be five, it could be 500,

00:49:28.660 --> 00:49:31.300
it could be minus 200.

00:49:31.300 --> 00:49:34.780
Minus 200 means that
you have short-sold

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:37.810
200 shares of that security.

00:49:37.810 --> 00:49:41.020
So these weights,
they all sum to one,

00:49:41.020 --> 00:49:43.480
but they don't have to
be all non-negative.

00:49:43.480 --> 00:49:45.370
Some of these weights
could be zero.

00:49:45.370 --> 00:49:49.450
Some of these weights
could be negative.

00:49:49.450 --> 00:49:52.249
If some of these weights
are negative, then

00:49:52.249 --> 00:49:54.290
what do you know about
some of the other weights?

00:49:57.540 --> 00:49:59.540
Well, yes, they have to
be positive because they

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:00.456
have to add up to one.

00:50:00.456 --> 00:50:03.647
But tell me more
about the weights.

00:50:03.647 --> 00:50:04.730
STUDENT: Greater than one.

00:50:04.730 --> 00:50:05.660
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:50:05.660 --> 00:50:08.510
Because in order
for it to add up

00:50:08.510 --> 00:50:11.520
to one, if some of these
things are less than zero, then

00:50:11.520 --> 00:50:13.520
some of these other things
are greater than one.

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:16.490
What does it mean for a
security to be greater than one,

00:50:16.490 --> 00:50:19.687
a weight to be greater than one?

00:50:19.687 --> 00:50:21.094
Does that make sense?

00:50:25.567 --> 00:50:26.650
What's the interpretation?

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:27.240
Yeah, Lucas?

00:50:27.240 --> 00:50:28.410
STUDENT: Does it mean
you're leveraged?

00:50:28.410 --> 00:50:30.160
PROFESSOR: It means
that you're leveraged,

00:50:30.160 --> 00:50:32.430
that's right-- leveraged
meaning that you're buying

00:50:32.430 --> 00:50:36.390
more than you have money.

00:50:36.390 --> 00:50:38.770
Where are you getting
that money from?

00:50:38.770 --> 00:50:43.644
You're basically getting
a loan, but who's

00:50:43.644 --> 00:50:44.560
loaning you the money?

00:50:47.130 --> 00:50:48.150
Andy?

00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:49.823
STUDENT: Well, the
stocks that you

00:50:49.823 --> 00:50:51.239
sold short gave
you the extra cash

00:50:51.239 --> 00:50:52.650
that you can buy long stock.

00:50:52.650 --> 00:50:53.650
PROFESSOR: That's right.

00:50:53.650 --> 00:50:59.940
So nobody loaned you money, but
somebody loaned you something.

00:50:59.940 --> 00:51:01.680
They loaned you a stock.

00:51:01.680 --> 00:51:05.160
So this simple little
framework already

00:51:05.160 --> 00:51:07.210
has given us one
interesting insight,

00:51:07.210 --> 00:51:12.000
which is that when we short sell
a stock and buy another one,

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:16.610
we're actually getting
a loan from somebody

00:51:16.610 --> 00:51:19.880
who's lending the stock
to us that we've sold.

00:51:19.880 --> 00:51:23.600
We've taken that cash and we're
putting it into another stock.

00:51:23.600 --> 00:51:27.320
So we're getting a
loan of one security

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:29.300
and turning around
and using those funds

00:51:29.300 --> 00:51:33.140
to buy another security.

00:51:33.140 --> 00:51:36.740
That's a new transaction
as far as we're concerned,

00:51:36.740 --> 00:51:40.130
but it's one that's going to be
very important in how we think

00:51:40.130 --> 00:51:42.420
about portfolio construction.

