00:53:51.710 --> 00:53:53.635
What's a 130-30 portfolio?

00:53:53.635 --> 00:53:55.010
Can you explain
that, or have you

00:53:55.010 --> 00:53:57.308
just heard that in the news?

00:53:57.308 --> 00:54:00.079
STUDENT: I understand, I
guess, the basic concept,

00:54:00.079 --> 00:54:04.154
which is you're 130%
long and are 30% short,

00:54:04.154 --> 00:54:06.452
so you're headed back to
a net exposure of zero.

00:54:06.452 --> 00:54:07.160
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:54:07.160 --> 00:54:08.180
That's right, exactly.

00:54:08.180 --> 00:54:10.130
So let me describe
a product that's

00:54:10.130 --> 00:54:13.350
out there that's been developed
just over the last few years.

00:54:13.350 --> 00:54:18.860
It's called a 130-30
portfolio, and what 130-30

00:54:18.860 --> 00:54:27.490
stands for is 130%
long and 30% short.

00:54:27.490 --> 00:54:31.030
Now, you can have
a 120-20 portfolio

00:54:31.030 --> 00:54:34.210
or a 180-80 portfolio.

00:54:34.210 --> 00:54:39.160
But the idea is that you have
weights that add up to 100%,

00:54:39.160 --> 00:54:45.220
but the long positions
are no greater than 130%.

00:54:45.220 --> 00:54:50.180
And the short positions
are no less than minus 30%.

00:54:50.180 --> 00:54:52.950
Now, the reason that this is an
interesting product is that--

00:54:52.950 --> 00:54:54.741
I have to give you a
little bit of history.

00:54:54.741 --> 00:54:57.250
This is getting a
little out of our area,

00:54:57.250 --> 00:55:01.650
but I'll give you a
preview of Investments 433.

00:55:01.650 --> 00:55:04.320
Typically, when
institutional investors

00:55:04.320 --> 00:55:07.330
like pension funds or mutual
funds, when they invest,

00:55:07.330 --> 00:55:10.061
they are not allowed
to short sell.

00:55:10.061 --> 00:55:11.560
This has nothing
to do with the SEC.

00:55:11.560 --> 00:55:13.290
It has nothing to do with law.

00:55:13.290 --> 00:55:15.690
It has to do with the
particular entities that

00:55:15.690 --> 00:55:19.065
are investing, because
short selling was viewed way

00:55:19.065 --> 00:55:22.800
back as being a very risky
endeavor because you could lose

00:55:22.800 --> 00:55:24.054
everything and more.

00:55:24.054 --> 00:55:25.470
There's unlimited
amounts that you

00:55:25.470 --> 00:55:28.560
could lose because your short
selling a stock can go way up

00:55:28.560 --> 00:55:31.380
and you could lose
tremendous amounts.

00:55:31.380 --> 00:55:34.500
So mutual funds
were originally not

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:37.120
allowed to short sell at all.

00:55:37.120 --> 00:55:40.020
So for a mutual fund,
the portfolio weights

00:55:40.020 --> 00:55:42.750
were restricted to
be non-negative,

00:55:42.750 --> 00:55:47.160
and certain pension funds were
not allowed to short sell.

00:55:47.160 --> 00:55:50.610
So if you were a pension
plan or a state university

00:55:50.610 --> 00:55:54.390
and you gave your money
to investment manager xyz,

00:55:54.390 --> 00:55:58.890
that investment manager would
be required not to short sell

00:55:58.890 --> 00:56:02.380
for your portfolio.

00:56:02.380 --> 00:56:05.350
It was discovered over
the last several years

00:56:05.350 --> 00:56:09.580
that this kind of
constraint artificially

00:56:09.580 --> 00:56:12.190
dampened the return
of a portfolio--

00:56:12.190 --> 00:56:14.770
not surprisingly, because
when the market goes down,

00:56:14.770 --> 00:56:18.160
if you're long-only
you're going down with it.

00:56:18.160 --> 00:56:20.200
But if you have a
short position, then

00:56:20.200 --> 00:56:24.040
at least the shorts would
be able to buffer some

00:56:24.040 --> 00:56:25.737
of the losses on the long side.

00:56:25.737 --> 00:56:27.820
So institutions have started
getting more and more

00:56:27.820 --> 00:56:30.032
sophisticated,
thanks to hedge funds

00:56:30.032 --> 00:56:31.990
pushing them into this
area because, of course,

00:56:31.990 --> 00:56:33.310
hedge funds can do anything.

00:56:33.310 --> 00:56:36.580
They can short, they can long,
they can go sideways, whatever.

00:56:36.580 --> 00:56:40.720
So hedge funds led
the pack by saying,

00:56:40.720 --> 00:56:42.520
we're going to
actually short sell

00:56:42.520 --> 00:56:44.440
some of your long-only
portfolio to help

00:56:44.440 --> 00:56:47.910
you get a little bit of
extra return on the downside.

00:56:47.910 --> 00:56:50.440
And so pretty soon,
institutional investors

00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:54.040
said, well, I actually
like the idea of you short

00:56:54.040 --> 00:56:56.702
selling a little bit but I don't
want you to do it too much.

00:56:56.702 --> 00:56:58.660
Because I don't really
know what the risks are.

00:56:58.660 --> 00:56:59.830
I'm new to this.

00:56:59.830 --> 00:57:02.830
I don't want to get the
risks out of control,

00:57:02.830 --> 00:57:05.770
so I'm going to limit how
much you can short sell.

00:57:05.770 --> 00:57:08.320
The limit of how much
you can short sell

00:57:08.320 --> 00:57:14.230
imposes a limit on how much
more long you can go than 100%.

00:57:14.230 --> 00:57:16.315
Just like we said, if
something's negative,

00:57:16.315 --> 00:57:18.690
then some of the weights have
got to be greater than one,

00:57:18.690 --> 00:57:20.710
or they got to add up
to greater than one.

00:57:20.710 --> 00:57:23.770
So when you have
that situation where

00:57:23.770 --> 00:57:28.450
you have a limit on the total
negative position you can have,

00:57:28.450 --> 00:57:32.830
that limit puts a symmetric
upper bound beyond the number

00:57:32.830 --> 00:57:36.250
one of what you can go long.

00:57:36.250 --> 00:57:40.390
And so for reasons that are
probably a little bit too far

00:57:40.390 --> 00:57:43.420
afield to get into
here, 130-30 seems

00:57:43.420 --> 00:57:46.510
to be a bit of a sweet spot
for managers out there.

00:57:46.510 --> 00:57:50.170
So they said, we will
limit our short positions

00:57:50.170 --> 00:57:53.200
to no more than
30% of the capital.

00:57:53.200 --> 00:57:55.930
So you give us $100
million to manage,

00:57:55.930 --> 00:57:59.980
we will take no more than
$30 million of shorts.

00:57:59.980 --> 00:58:03.580
And therefore, we will take
no more than $130 million

00:58:03.580 --> 00:58:04.840
of longs.

00:58:04.840 --> 00:58:08.540
But when you add them up,
you still get back to 100%.

00:58:08.540 --> 00:58:09.370
So that's 130-30.

00:58:09.370 --> 00:58:11.650
It's very popular,
and it's something

00:58:11.650 --> 00:58:14.230
that is likely to grow,
particularly given

00:58:14.230 --> 00:58:15.580
this current market environment.

00:58:15.580 --> 00:58:20.390
Because 130-30 has done better
than the S&amp;P, not surprisingly,

00:58:20.390 --> 00:58:24.780
because of that
30% short position.

00:58:24.780 --> 00:58:28.560
So here's the example
of your own portfolio

00:58:28.560 --> 00:58:29.880
and how you get those weights.

00:58:29.880 --> 00:58:32.500
That's pretty straightforward.

