01:05:48.780 --> 01:05:52.410
how do I construct one
of these good portfolios?

01:05:52.410 --> 01:05:54.436
And in order to
answer that question,

01:05:54.436 --> 01:05:56.060
I've got to tell you
what "good" means,

01:05:56.060 --> 01:05:58.200
or you've got to tell
me what "good" means.

01:05:58.200 --> 01:06:03.090
So typically, what we say
about a good portfolio

01:06:03.090 --> 01:06:11.400
is it's a portfolio that
has high mean and low risk.

01:06:11.400 --> 01:06:13.080
That's what "good" means.

01:06:13.080 --> 01:06:16.560
There are two characteristics
that we tend to focus on

01:06:16.560 --> 01:06:19.530
for purely statistical reasons.

01:06:19.530 --> 01:06:22.060
It's because those
are easy to compute,

01:06:22.060 --> 01:06:24.270
and they are the
first two statistics

01:06:24.270 --> 01:06:25.740
that one would
look at when you're

01:06:25.740 --> 01:06:27.900
looking at an
investment-- the mean

01:06:27.900 --> 01:06:29.920
and the standard deviation.

01:06:29.920 --> 01:06:32.670
So you might think that,
naturally, it would make sense

01:06:32.670 --> 01:06:35.430
to pick a portfolio
that's got high mean

01:06:35.430 --> 01:06:37.770
and low standard deviation.

01:06:37.770 --> 01:06:39.162
That's an assumption.

01:06:39.162 --> 01:06:40.870
In other words, we're
assuming that we're

01:06:40.870 --> 01:06:44.100
going to measure risk
by standard deviation,

01:06:44.100 --> 01:06:46.600
and we're assuming that
we're measuring return

01:06:46.600 --> 01:06:49.390
by the actual expected
rate of return.

