01:07:03.610 --> 01:07:08.200
that engage in nonunion
workers, or they

01:07:08.200 --> 01:07:09.790
don't want to
invest in companies

01:07:09.790 --> 01:07:15.590
that happen to be exploiting
labor in unregulated markets.

01:07:15.590 --> 01:07:18.460
Those are examples of
non-pecuniary characteristics

01:07:18.460 --> 01:07:21.190
that figure into this
choice of stocks.

01:07:21.190 --> 01:07:22.910
We're going to
abstract from that.

01:07:22.910 --> 01:07:25.660
So for our purposes, the
characteristics that we're

01:07:25.660 --> 01:07:27.790
going to look at
for a good portfolio

01:07:27.790 --> 01:07:31.840
is, does it have a high
return, does it have low risk?

01:07:31.840 --> 01:07:33.910
And the way we're
going to measure risk

01:07:33.910 --> 01:07:38.750
is in terms of the volatility
or standard deviation.

01:07:38.750 --> 01:07:42.820
Now, here, again, there's lots
of ways of measuring risk.

01:07:42.820 --> 01:07:47.820
We can measure by the
upper quartile, the 5% loss

01:07:47.820 --> 01:07:51.370
or spread, but in fact,
what we're going to use

01:07:51.370 --> 01:07:53.890
is this standard
deviation measure.

01:07:53.890 --> 01:07:56.080
For symmetric distributions
like the normal,

01:07:56.080 --> 01:07:59.800
it turns out that that's
not a bad measure,

01:07:59.800 --> 01:08:03.310
but some people have argued
that by looking at spread

01:08:03.310 --> 01:08:07.240
you're confusing the
upside with the downside.

01:08:07.240 --> 01:08:11.780
Nobody has any problem
with upside risk or upside

01:08:11.780 --> 01:08:15.217
distribution.

01:08:15.217 --> 01:08:17.050
I haven't run across
anybody that said, gee,

01:08:17.050 --> 01:08:19.340
this year I'm really
making too much money

01:08:19.340 --> 01:08:20.979
and that's just
not a good thing.

01:08:20.979 --> 01:08:23.290
If you meet anybody
like that, introduce me.

01:08:23.290 --> 01:08:26.200
I'll help them out
with their problem.

01:08:26.200 --> 01:08:29.560
But the point is that for
a symmetric distribution,

01:08:29.560 --> 01:08:34.450
it doesn't matter, and in
more advanced approaches

01:08:34.450 --> 01:08:38.080
to investments people have
used one-sided measures.

01:08:38.080 --> 01:08:40.326
But we're not going to
do that in this course.

01:08:40.326 --> 01:08:42.700
So we're going to focus on
variance or standard deviation

01:08:42.700 --> 01:08:46.160
as the measure of risk.

01:08:46.160 --> 01:08:48.080
And the assumptions
that I'm going

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:50.990
to make for the
remainder of the course

01:08:50.990 --> 01:08:59.760
is that all investors like
higher mean and all investors

01:08:59.760 --> 01:09:03.840
like higher variance.

01:09:03.840 --> 01:09:08.040
Now, that's a really
reasonable assumption,

01:09:08.040 --> 01:09:10.800
but you could
challenge it if you

01:09:10.800 --> 01:09:14.609
wanted to argue that investors
care about other things.

01:09:14.609 --> 01:09:18.120
So just be aware that I'm
making an approximation,

01:09:18.120 --> 01:09:21.479
and the approximation is exactly
that, that mean and variance

01:09:21.479 --> 01:09:25.710
are the only things that
our prototypical investor is

01:09:25.710 --> 01:09:28.670
going to care about.

01:09:28.670 --> 01:09:31.280
So now, we actually are
pretty close to being

01:09:31.280 --> 01:09:33.529
able to come up with an
answer to the question, what's

01:09:33.529 --> 01:09:37.818
a good portfolio and
how do we pick stocks.

01:09:37.818 --> 01:09:39.859
One of the things that
we're going to answer over

01:09:39.859 --> 01:09:41.240
the course of the
next few slides

01:09:41.240 --> 01:09:45.620
is, how much does
a stock contribute

01:09:45.620 --> 01:09:50.460
to the risk and the expected
return of a portfolio?

01:09:50.460 --> 01:09:53.750
So if you're thinking about
investing in a new stock,

01:09:53.750 --> 01:09:58.682
it's like inviting
somebody into your club.

01:09:58.682 --> 01:10:00.140
You want to ask,
well, what are you

01:10:00.140 --> 01:10:01.717
going to contribute to my club?

01:10:01.717 --> 01:10:03.800
What are you going to
contribute to the portfolio?

01:10:03.800 --> 01:10:05.990
What will you add to
what I already have?

01:10:05.990 --> 01:10:08.480
Are you going to help me
with my expected return?

01:10:08.480 --> 01:10:10.910
Are you going to help
me lower my risk?

01:10:10.910 --> 01:10:13.556
And if the answer is no to both
of them, then I don't want you.

01:10:13.556 --> 01:10:15.180
You're not going to
do anything for me.

01:10:15.180 --> 01:10:16.760
Why should you be
in my portfolio?

01:10:16.760 --> 01:10:18.260
So that's the kind
of argument we're

01:10:18.260 --> 01:10:22.940
going to make to be able to
construct a good portfolio.

01:10:22.940 --> 01:10:26.550
So let's get a little bit
more specific about that.

01:10:26.550 --> 01:10:29.930
Here's a graph, and you're
going to see this a lot.

01:10:29.930 --> 01:10:32.390
This graph is going
to be one that we use

01:10:32.390 --> 01:10:34.810
for all of portfolio analysis.

01:10:34.810 --> 01:10:38.240
It's where we plot on
two-dimensional space

01:10:38.240 --> 01:10:41.780
the average return
of the stock as well

01:10:41.780 --> 01:10:44.540
as its risk, where
risk is now being

01:10:44.540 --> 01:10:47.720
measured by standard deviation.

01:10:47.720 --> 01:10:51.500
So I've got five
assets plotted here.

01:10:51.500 --> 01:10:55.070
Merck is one and General
Motors is another one.

01:10:55.070 --> 01:10:57.440
Motorola is a third,
McDonald's a fourth,

01:10:57.440 --> 01:11:01.600
and I've got T-bills down
there on the lower left.

01:11:01.600 --> 01:11:06.130
This gives you a sense of the
different trade-offs there are.

01:11:06.130 --> 01:11:11.350
Clearly General Motors is
lower risk that Motorola,

01:11:11.350 --> 01:11:13.920
but it's also lower return.

01:11:13.920 --> 01:11:17.220
And McDonald's is
definitely going

01:11:17.220 --> 01:11:24.960
to be higher risk than Merck,
but notice that McDonald's is

01:11:24.960 --> 01:11:28.450
also lower return than Merck.

01:11:28.450 --> 01:11:34.410
So at least in this setting,
nobody in their right mind--

01:11:34.410 --> 01:11:36.480
by that I mean, no
rational investor--

01:11:36.480 --> 01:11:41.130
would ever want to hold
McDonald's over Merck--

01:11:41.130 --> 01:11:44.160
by our assumption.

01:11:44.160 --> 01:11:50.250
We're assuming that investors
like expected return

01:11:50.250 --> 01:11:53.160
and they don't like risk.

01:11:53.160 --> 01:11:53.660
Question?

01:11:53.660 --> 01:11:54.508
Yeah?

01:11:54.508 --> 01:11:57.992
STUDENT: This [INAUDIBLE]
think that McDonald's will

01:11:57.992 --> 01:11:58.617
perform better.

01:11:58.617 --> 01:11:59.992
PROFESSOR: Exactly,
that's right.

01:11:59.992 --> 01:12:01.926
So I was waiting for
somebody to say that.

01:12:01.926 --> 01:12:03.800
Warren Buffett would
say that's the stupidest

01:12:03.800 --> 01:12:07.790
thing I've ever heard,
because all you're doing

01:12:07.790 --> 01:12:10.850
is plotting history
on this chart.

01:12:10.850 --> 01:12:13.610
And this tells you nothing
about what might happen

01:12:13.610 --> 01:12:16.610
over the next 12, 24 months.

01:12:16.610 --> 01:12:20.090
It could be that health
care is going to just become

01:12:20.090 --> 01:12:22.430
a real problem,
pharmaceutical companies

01:12:22.430 --> 01:12:24.080
are going to get
battered because

01:12:24.080 --> 01:12:25.730
of the Democratic
administration.

01:12:25.730 --> 01:12:28.400
That's going to force
them to reduce the prices.

01:12:28.400 --> 01:12:30.185
And so over the next
six to 12 months,

01:12:30.185 --> 01:12:32.060
the only thing that
people will be able to do

01:12:32.060 --> 01:12:35.300
is to go to their neighborhood
McDonald's and just enjoy

01:12:35.300 --> 01:12:37.760
a nice hamburger and
complain about what's

01:12:37.760 --> 01:12:40.940
been going on with the
pharmaceutical industry.

01:12:40.940 --> 01:12:42.890
In that case, McDonald's
is a great bet

01:12:42.890 --> 01:12:45.740
and Merck is a
terrible investment.

01:12:45.740 --> 01:12:47.740
We abstract from all of that.

01:12:47.740 --> 01:12:50.930
We are not in the business
of forecasting stock returns.

01:12:50.930 --> 01:12:51.530
Why?

01:12:51.530 --> 01:12:53.660
Because I just showed you
in the previous set of

01:12:53.660 --> 01:12:56.360
slides that it's
hard to forecast.

01:12:56.360 --> 01:12:58.970
In fact, you told me that
in an efficient market

01:12:58.970 --> 01:13:00.710
it's actually hard
to tell what's going

01:13:00.710 --> 01:13:01.990
to happen with these stocks.

01:13:01.990 --> 01:13:03.500
And if you could
tell, then people

01:13:03.500 --> 01:13:05.490
are going to start
using that information,

01:13:05.490 --> 01:13:07.370
and then the
information is worthless

01:13:07.370 --> 01:13:10.190
because it'll have already
been taken into account.

01:13:10.190 --> 01:13:13.750
So you see, this
is a very important

01:13:13.750 --> 01:13:17.950
philosophical difference between
Warren Buffett and academics.

01:13:17.950 --> 01:13:19.840
Warren Buffett
believes that there

01:13:19.840 --> 01:13:23.350
are systematic mispricings
out there that can be

01:13:23.350 --> 01:13:26.400
found and taken advantage of.

01:13:26.400 --> 01:13:29.400
Academic finance, as
of the 1960s and 70s

01:13:29.400 --> 01:13:32.380
when this theory was developed,
started from the point

01:13:32.380 --> 01:13:35.140
that you just came
to very quickly,

01:13:35.140 --> 01:13:38.200
which is that there are
no patterns in the data.

01:13:38.200 --> 01:13:41.660
If there were, someone
would have already done it--

01:13:41.660 --> 01:13:44.390
which, by the way, Warren
Buffett would answer by saying,

01:13:44.390 --> 01:13:46.850
you know what, that sounds
like a joke about the economist

01:13:46.850 --> 01:13:49.460
walking down the road,
sees a $100 bill,

01:13:49.460 --> 01:13:50.377
and walks right by it.

01:13:50.377 --> 01:13:51.959
And when somebody
says, why didn't you

01:13:51.959 --> 01:13:54.440
pick up the $100 bill, they
said, well, if it were real,

01:13:54.440 --> 01:13:58.100
someone would have
already picked it up.

01:13:58.100 --> 01:14:00.230
I mean, that's the argument
that we made together.

01:14:00.230 --> 01:14:02.990
We made that argument, that if
there was a pattern somebody

01:14:02.990 --> 01:14:04.948
would take advantage of
it and then the pattern

01:14:04.948 --> 01:14:06.860
can't be there.

01:14:06.860 --> 01:14:08.360
And then, again,
Warren Buffet would

01:14:08.360 --> 01:14:10.235
say, that's the stupidest
thing I ever heard,

01:14:10.235 --> 01:14:12.890
because in fact, I've done
it, I saw the patterns,

01:14:12.890 --> 01:14:15.290
I took advantage of it,
and I have a bit more money

01:14:15.290 --> 01:14:18.680
than you do, so there.

01:14:18.680 --> 01:14:19.690
Who do you believe?

01:14:19.690 --> 01:14:22.940
Well, it's kind of hard to
argue with a $40-something

01:14:22.940 --> 01:14:24.860
billionaire.

01:14:24.860 --> 01:14:28.010
I think that's his
wealth, $40 billion.

01:14:28.010 --> 01:14:31.370
But that's not the
perspective of this analysis.

01:14:31.370 --> 01:14:32.296
Mike?

01:14:32.296 --> 01:14:34.797
STUDENT: Well, let's say
the expected return was

01:14:34.797 --> 01:14:36.380
you had perfect
information and that's

01:14:36.380 --> 01:14:38.215
what was going to be a
perfect crystal ball.

01:14:38.215 --> 01:14:40.922
It would still be irrational
to buy McDonald's versus

01:14:40.922 --> 01:14:44.978
Merck, so you'd short
McDonald's and long Merck

01:14:44.978 --> 01:14:46.310
until the returns became equal.

01:14:46.310 --> 01:14:46.820
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:14:46.820 --> 01:14:49.010
So I'm going to talk about
that for a little while,

01:14:49.010 --> 01:14:49.730
but you're right.

01:14:49.730 --> 01:14:52.790
So if you could short,
then what you'd want to do

01:14:52.790 --> 01:14:53.990
is exactly what you said.

01:14:53.990 --> 01:14:59.540
You want to basically long the
low risk, high yield asset,

01:14:59.540 --> 01:15:03.350
short the high risk, low
yield asset, make that spread,

01:15:03.350 --> 01:15:05.599
and make it as
riskless as you can

01:15:05.599 --> 01:15:06.890
buy including other securities.

01:15:06.890 --> 01:15:07.715
Yes?

01:15:07.715 --> 01:15:09.715
STUDENT: Yeah, but
eventually it would collapse,

01:15:09.715 --> 01:15:11.090
and then the
relationship would--

01:15:11.090 --> 01:15:12.339
PROFESSOR: And then it should.

01:15:12.339 --> 01:15:12.920
That's right.

01:15:12.920 --> 01:15:16.460
So the argument that
economists would make

01:15:16.460 --> 01:15:21.540
is that this picture is
the equilibrium of where

01:15:21.540 --> 01:15:26.580
these returns should be, given
what the market determines

01:15:26.580 --> 01:15:31.030
their fair rates of return
are, relative to their risks.

01:15:31.030 --> 01:15:33.960
So that's, again, a very big
philosophical difference.

01:15:33.960 --> 01:15:36.720
An economist would say,
all of these securities

01:15:36.720 --> 01:15:38.940
are exactly where
they should be.

01:15:38.940 --> 01:15:43.560
And they may change over
time, but at any point in time

01:15:43.560 --> 01:15:45.240
they are where they should be.

01:15:45.240 --> 01:15:48.540
Supply equals demand,
market's clear,

01:15:48.540 --> 01:15:53.200
everything is equilibrium,
and our decision

01:15:53.200 --> 01:15:56.020
is simply to figure
out what to make

01:15:56.020 --> 01:15:59.230
of the portfolio of
these securities.

01:15:59.230 --> 01:16:02.750
What is the best portfolio
of these securities?

01:16:02.750 --> 01:16:05.426
So I'm just warning you, this
is a philosophical departure

01:16:05.426 --> 01:16:07.300
from what you're used
to thinking and reading

01:16:07.300 --> 01:16:08.050
in the newspapers.

01:16:08.050 --> 01:16:09.741
Because the newspapers
would say, well,

01:16:09.741 --> 01:16:11.740
let's take a look at the
earnings at McDonald's.

01:16:11.740 --> 01:16:12.790
Let's take a look at Merck.

01:16:12.790 --> 01:16:14.020
Let's talk to the
macroeconomists

01:16:14.020 --> 01:16:15.760
and see what's going to happen
over the next 12 months.

01:16:15.760 --> 01:16:16.980
Let's talk to the
earnings analysts

01:16:16.980 --> 01:16:18.896
and see whether they
forecast higher earnings,

01:16:18.896 --> 01:16:20.020
lower earnings.

01:16:20.020 --> 01:16:22.900
The whole point of the academic
infrastructure that we set up

01:16:22.900 --> 01:16:26.110
is that you can't
predict these things.

01:16:26.110 --> 01:16:28.360
And if you believe that,
then basically Warren Buffett

01:16:28.360 --> 01:16:31.660
is just one really lucky guy.

01:16:31.660 --> 01:16:37.450
So I'm going to have to justify
this academic position to you.

01:16:37.450 --> 01:16:39.987
And I won't do that until
the end of the semester,

01:16:39.987 --> 01:16:42.320
because first of all, I have
a lot of material to cover.

01:16:42.320 --> 01:16:45.280
And I want to cover all of the
material in the basic form,

01:16:45.280 --> 01:16:48.280
and then in the end I'm going
to give you a sense of where

01:16:48.280 --> 01:16:49.930
things really stand.

01:16:49.930 --> 01:16:50.900
It's a fiction.

01:16:50.900 --> 01:16:54.710
It's a fiction that you
can't forecast stock prices,

01:16:54.710 --> 01:16:58.150
but it's a fiction that actually
is pretty close to reality

01:16:58.150 --> 01:17:00.730
for 99% of the public.

01:17:00.730 --> 01:17:03.560
Now, you guys are not
99% of the public.

01:17:03.560 --> 01:17:05.770
But for the people
that will someday

01:17:05.770 --> 01:17:08.950
be your clients
or your investors,

01:17:08.950 --> 01:17:12.010
it will be true, that
the typical individual

01:17:12.010 --> 01:17:15.850
has no hope of being able to
out-forecast Warren Buffett.

01:17:15.850 --> 01:17:17.860
And if you can't
out-forecast somebody,

01:17:17.860 --> 01:17:20.320
then you may as well
assume that they're random

01:17:20.320 --> 01:17:23.590
and they're perfectly priced.

01:17:23.590 --> 01:17:25.330
And then you still
have the problem, OK,

01:17:25.330 --> 01:17:27.667
if you assume that,
then what do you do?

01:17:27.667 --> 01:17:29.500
That's all we're going
to try to figure out.

01:17:29.500 --> 01:17:33.890
I'm going to tell you what
you do with portfolio theory.

01:17:33.890 --> 01:17:36.580
Now, since we're
almost out of time,

01:17:36.580 --> 01:17:38.330
I want to just tell
you where we're going.

01:17:38.330 --> 01:17:40.580
What we're going to do
is look at this graph

01:17:40.580 --> 01:17:45.230
and ask the question,
what do people want?

01:17:45.230 --> 01:17:48.590
They want higher return,
they want to go north,

01:17:48.590 --> 01:17:50.120
and they want lower risk.

01:17:50.120 --> 01:17:52.220
They want to go west.

01:17:52.220 --> 01:17:54.350
So the northwest is
where we're going

01:17:54.350 --> 01:17:57.110
to be heading in this
graph, and the question

01:17:57.110 --> 01:17:58.970
is, how can we get there?

01:17:58.970 --> 01:18:01.820
How can we get as
northwest as possible

01:18:01.820 --> 01:18:03.140
using these securities?

01:18:03.140 --> 01:18:05.090
And the answer will
shock you, I think,

01:18:05.090 --> 01:18:07.570
because you're going
to see that by doing

01:18:07.570 --> 01:18:10.190
a very simple little bit
of high school algebra

01:18:10.190 --> 01:18:12.740
we can actually create
a portfolio that

01:18:12.740 --> 01:18:15.020
beats all of these things.

01:18:15.020 --> 01:18:17.600
That is, if you
didn't know anything

01:18:17.600 --> 01:18:21.170
about portfolio theory, you
would be severely worse off,

01:18:21.170 --> 01:18:24.119
because you'd be stuck having to
be on one of these five points.

01:18:24.119 --> 01:18:25.910
And if you knew a little
bit of high school

01:18:25.910 --> 01:18:29.550
algebra and some finance, you
could actually do a lot better.

01:18:29.550 --> 01:18:32.230
So we'll see that on Monday.

